</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B84525DFFDDA44BFCCDB5990459FEC4" blockId="24.[809,1424,197,311]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">
<materialsCitation id="3B535800FFDDA44BFCCDB5990459FEC4" collectionCode="EGPPA-MPTA" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
<emphasis id="B94F8E4FFFDDA44BFCCDB59902D2FF29" box="[809,926,197,218]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">
<typeStatus id="5480ECFFFFDDA44BFCCDB59902DBFF29" box="[809,919,197,218]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">Holotype</typeStatus>
:
</emphasis>
Specimen 
<emphasis id="B94F8E4FFFDDA44BFBDEB59905F5FF29" box="[1082,1209,197,218]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">207.13307</emphasis>
of the inventory of 
<collectionCode id="ED2ACA98FFDDA44BFCACB5B802BBFF0A" box="[840,1015,228,249]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">EGPPA-MPTA</collectionCode>
institution in Asti. The specimen includes most of the skull, with one periotic in articulation, seven vertebrae and nine ribs.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B84525DFFDDA44BFCCDB43C028AF96F" blockId="24.[809,1425,352,1692]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">
<emphasis id="B94F8E4FFFDDA44BFCCDB43C0578FE86" box="[809,1076,352,373]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">Horizon and locality:</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus id="5480ECFFFFDDA44BFB9FB43C05A8FE85" box="[1147,1252,352,374]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">holotype</typeStatus>
skeleton was discovered near San Marzanotto dâ€™Asti (~ 
<quantity id="4CC3FFB8FFDDA44BFAABB42204DCFE67" box="[1359,1424,382,404]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" unit="km" value="6.0">6 km</quantity>
South from Asti, 
<collectingRegion id="49FF9CBFFFDDA44BFBE3B4C105CDFE40" box="[1031,1153,413,435]" country="Italy" name="Piemonte" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">Piedmont</collectingRegion>
, northern 
<collectingCountry id="F32C12CDFFDDA44BFAEFB4C10406FE40" box="[1291,1354,413,435]" name="Italy" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">Italy</collectingCountry>
). The geographical coordinates of the site of the discovery are 
<geoCoordinate id="EE0F349AFFDDA44BFCBFB4860546FE03" box="[859,1034,473,496]" degrees="44" direction="north" minutes="51" orientation="latitude" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" precision="1" seconds="54.36" value="44.865097">44Â°51â€²54.36â€³N</geoCoordinate>
and 
<geoCoordinate id="EE0F349AFFDDA44BFBA9B48705A0FE03" box="[1101,1260,473,496]" degrees="8" direction="east" minutes="13" orientation="longitude" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" precision="1" seconds="13.33" value="8.220369">8Â°13â€²13.33â€³E</geoCoordinate>
(
<figureCitation id="13004ED8FFDDA44BFAE4B486040BFE03" box="[1280,1351,474,496]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="1.[827,906,1251,1273]" captionTargetBox="[895,1375,195,1211]" captionTargetId="figure-684@1.[895,1375,195,1211]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figure 1. Map showing the discovery site of the holotype skeleton of Marzanoptera tersillae. A, the Italian peninsula. B, the locality of the discovery. The arrow indicates the site of San Marzanotto, which is located ~5 km South from Asti." pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA2FACFFDDA44BFABCB48602B0FDFD" author="Boni A &amp; Casnedi R" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" refId="ref23268" refString="Boni A, Casnedi R. 1970. Note illustrative della Carta d'Italia. F. 69. Asti, Roma: ISPRA." type="book" year="1970">Boni &amp; Casnedi, 1970</bibRefCitation>
). The specimen was found in a hilly area in Asti Province, a site previously known because of the discovery of several marine mammals, including an almost complete, 9-m-long skeleton of a large balaenopterid whale assigned to â€˜ 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B29DEFFDDA44BFB11B728056FFD5B" authorityName="' (Caretto" authorityYear="1970" class="Mammalia" family="Balaenopteridae" genus="Balaenoptera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cetacea" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="acutorostrata" subSpecies="cuvieri">
<emphasis id="B94F8E4FFFDDA44BFB11B728056FFD5B" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">Balaenoptera acutorostrata cuvieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
â€™ by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA2FACFFDDA44BFBB2B7CF0448FD5A" author="Caretto PG" box="[1110,1284,659,681]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" pagination="3 - 75" refId="ref23606" refString="Caretto PG. 1970. La balenottera delle sabbie plioceniche di Valmontasca (Vigliano d'Asti). Bollettino della Societa Paleontologica Italiana 9: 3 - 75." type="journal article" year="1970">Caretto (1970)</bibRefCitation>
, which was discovered in Valmontasca (Vigliano dâ€™Asti). That skeleton was subsequently regarded as a new taxon (still to be described formally) by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA2FACFFDDA44BFB53B7B20425FCF6" author="Bisconti M" box="[1207,1385,750,773]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" pagination="147 - 156" refId="ref22590" refString="Bisconti M. 2009. Taxonomy and evolution of the Italian Pliocene Mysticeti (Mammalia, Cetacea): a state of the art. Bollettino della Societa Paleontologica Italiana 48: 147 - 156." type="journal article" year="2009">Bisconti (2009)</bibRefCitation>
. In this area, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA2FACFFDDA44BFC42B651051AFCD0" author="Caretto PG" box="[934,1110,781,803]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" pagination="3 - 75" refId="ref23606" refString="Caretto PG. 1970. La balenottera delle sabbie plioceniche di Valmontasca (Vigliano d'Asti). Bollettino della Societa Paleontologica Italiana 9: 3 - 75." type="journal article" year="1970">Caretto (1970)</bibRefCitation>
described a stratigraphic sequence ~ 
<quantity id="4CC3FFB8FFDDA44BFC42B67002ACFCB2" box="[934,992,812,834]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.3" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" unit="m" value="53.0">53 m</quantity>
thick. At the bottom of this sequence, there are 
<quantity id="4CC3FFB8FFDDA44BFC73B616028DFC93" box="[919,961,842,864]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" unit="m" value="5.0">5 m</quantity>
of clayey sediments in Piacenzian facies, overlapped by ~ 
<quantity id="4CC3FFB8FFDDA44BFC01B635056CFC8C" box="[997,1056,873,895]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" unit="m" value="48.0">48 m</quantity>
of sands alternating with silty sand. In this second part, there are two layers with abundant molluscs, dominated by bivalves (Supporting Information, 
<tableCitation id="C6B967E6FFDDA44BFC2AB6990577FC29" box="[974,1083,965,987]" captionStart="Table S" captionStartId="39.[163,233,658,679]" captionText="Table S1. List of molluscan taxa found in close association with the holotype skeleton of Marzanoptera tersillae. Table S2. Measurements of the holotype skull of Marzanoptera tersillae (EGPPA-MPTA No. 207.13307, Asti). Measurements are in millimetres. Numbers on the right are from the right side; numbers on the left are from the left side." pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">Table S1</tableCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="13004ED8FFDDA44BFBA8B69905E8FC29" box="[1100,1188,965,987]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="1.[827,906,1251,1273]" captionTargetBox="[895,1375,195,1211]" captionTargetId="figure-684@1.[895,1375,195,1211]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figure 1. Map showing the discovery site of the holotype skeleton of Marzanoptera tersillae. A, the Italian peninsula. B, the locality of the discovery. The arrow indicates the site of San Marzanotto, which is located ~5 km South from Asti." pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">Fig. S1</figureCitation>
). Polychaete tubes (
<taxonomicName id="4C3B29DEFFDDA44BFCD5B6B80544FC0A" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1767" box="[817,1032,996,1018]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Ditrupa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="cornea">
<emphasis id="B94F8E4FFFDDA44BFCD5B6B802C3FC0A" box="[817,911,996,1017]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">Ditrupa</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis id="B94F8E4FFFDDA44BFC5FB6B80544FC0A" box="[955,1032,996,1017]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">cornea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) are also abundant in this fossil community lying beneath and near the bones. The particular diagenetic conditions associated with the water circulation in the sediments did not allow the preservation of the calcareous tests of foraminiferans except in a few cases. The few foraminiferans found showed worn tests and unrecognizable morphological features. Therefore, the study of the foraminiferans found at the site did not allow an accurate stratigraphic reconstruction. To obtain a more accurate chronostratigraphic assessment of the site, the mollusc assemblage was compared with assemblages from other sites of the Asti area where foraminiferans were more abundant (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA2FACFFDDA44BFC1CB02E05E0FA74" author="Scarselli S" box="[1016,1196,1394,1416]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" refId="ref26574" refString="Scarselli S. 1990. Variazioni nelle malacofaune piloceniche della sommita delle Argille di Lugagnano ad Ovest di Asti. Unpublished MSc Thesis, Universita di Torino." type="book" year="1990">Scarselli, 1990</bibRefCitation>
). This comparison resulted in the conclusion that the whale-bearing horizon corresponds approximately to the higher part of the Argille Azzurre Formation, close to the overlying Sabbie dâ€™Asti Formation (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA2FACFFDDA44BFBB4B0B105A3F9F0" author="Carraro F" box="[1104,1263,1517,1539]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" pagination="36 - 38" refId="ref23634" refString="Carraro F. 1996. Revisione del Villafranchiano nell'area-tipo di Villafranca d'Asti. Il Quaternario 9: 36 - 38." type="journal article" year="1996">Carraro, 1996</bibRefCitation>
). The mollusc assemblage and the overall stratigraphic data support the hypothesis that the estimated age of the whale-bearing horizon is earliest Piacenzian, MPL4a foraminiferal zone of 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA2FACFFDDA44BFBCCB33405A8F98D" author="Rio D &amp; Channell JET &amp; Bertoldi R &amp; Poli MS &amp; Vergerio PP &amp; Raffi I &amp; Sprovieri R &amp; Thunell RC" box="[1064,1252,1640,1662]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277" pagination="1 - 25" refId="ref26475" refString="Rio D, Channell JET, Bertoldi R, Poli MS, Vergerio PP, Raffi I, Sprovieri R, Thunell RC. 1997. Pliocene sapropels in the northern Adriatic area: chronology and paleoenvironmental significance. Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology 135: 1 - 25." type="journal article" year="1997">
Rio 
<emphasis id="B94F8E4FFFDDA44BFBB3B33405DEF98E" box="[1111,1170,1640,1661]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="1277">et al.</emphasis>
(1997)
</bibRefCitation>
(between ~3.6 and 3.2 Mya).
</paragraph>
